Hi team/community. I have a question and constructive criticism/concern and am curious to hear thoughts on this. I posted this in the telegram and got great feedback and it was suggested to post it here.

If chattensor is programmed to "decline inappropriate requests", isn't that centralization? I agree it'd be nice if people don't submit prompts for child porn, how to make bombs, etc., but isn't allowing anything true decentralization? For certain things to be blocked, a singular entity is deciding what is considered "inappropriate requests". 

It's such a slippery slope. Maybe today the things flagged/blocked are considered to make sense, but who's to say that after a few years of employee turnover at bittensor foundation there are people with different opinions that change those rules and block the same types of prompts that are currently blocked by chatgpt under the premise of them being "inappropriate requests"? How can bittensor be called truly decentralized while a single entity decides which prompts/uses are ok and which aren't?
chattensor isn't bittensor. it's a single proof-of-concept app.
and it's not even beta released yet.
If you have a validator, you can make apps on the network and you can make them as censored or uncensored as you want.
sounds like decentralization to me.

(I'd also argue that "decentralization" doesn't preclude content restrictions at all, but then we just descend into tedious semantics about a word (decentralization) that means a lot of different things to different people.)
Me too Mr Cole
good point. its decentralized and allows the market to decide what they want to use

I'm strongly pro-decentralization, but I don't think it would come as a surprise to many here that I'm not an ancap or libertarian about this stuff. Not into arguing it on the internet, though, so if you disagree, that's cool with me. If we're ever in person having a beer or something I'm happy to discuss whatever, though :cheers:
